## Interview Corner

**Q: We do code review — why do we need automated Dockerfile linting?**
Code review focuses on application logic. Reviewers rarely scrutinise Dockerfile instructions at the rule level — a missing USER directive buried in 40 lines of RUN commands gets approved because the reviewer doesn't know DL3002. hadolint applies 50+ rules consistently on every commit, in under a second, with no reviewer fatigue. It catches things humans reliably miss.

**Q: hadolint missed the missing USER in Lab 01 — should we still use it?**
Yes. hadolint DL3002 fires when USER root is explicit. It misses the case where USER is absent entirely. This is a known gap — documented in Phase 1 — and is why we pair hadolint with dockle. Each tool catches what the other misses. The gap does not invalidate hadolint's value for the 50+ other rules it does catch reliably.

**Q: Where in the Jenkins pipeline should hadolint run?**
As the very first stage, before docker build. It costs nothing — hadolint reads the Dockerfile text, no network calls, no image pulls, runs in under a second. If linting fails, you save the time of building, pushing, and scanning a vulnerable image. Shift-left means catching issues at the cheapest possible point.

